Here's an example of how a table of contents can be generated automatically in a LaTeX document using the `toc` command:
```
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{lipsum}
\begin{document}
\section{Introduction}
This section introduces the topic of our paper.
\subsection{Background}
The background section provides a brief overview of the existing literature on the subject matter.
\subsubsection{Related Work}
There have been several studies that address the same problem as our paper, including \cite{example1}, \cite{example2}, and \cite{example3}.
\subsection{Methodology}
The methodology section describes the approach we took to solve the problem, including the data collection, analysis, and modeling techniques used.
\subsubsection{Results}
The results section presents the findings of our study, including the key results and any limitations or challenges faced.
\section{Discussion}
This section discusses the implications of our findings and presents potential future directions for research.
\subsection{Conclusion}
The conclusion section summarizes the main points of the paper and emphasizes the significance of our work.
\tableofcontents
\end{document}
```
In this example, the `tableofcontents` command is placed at the beginning of the document using the `begin{document}` command. The `toc` environment is then used to generate the table of contents, which is a list of all the sections, subsections, and subsubsections in the document. The `\section` command is used to create a new section, the `\subsection` command to create a new subsection, and the `\subsubsection` command to create a new subsubsection. The `\tableofcontents` command is used to display the list of contents in the document.
Note that the `lipsum` package is used to generate some sample text for the introduction and conclusion sections, but you can replace it with your own content. The `example` environment is used to create an example of a section with a title, and the `\section` and `\subsection` commands are used to create subsections with titles. The `\subsubsection` command is used to create subsubsections with titles. Finally, the `\tableofcontents` command is used to display the list of contents in the document.

